A Republican Strategy to Confront Obama's Re-election
Republican leaders justify their policies by citing the need to combat voter fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by affirming that voter fraud in the U.S. is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning.
By the way, the lawyers of the Republicans have recorded only 300 cases of voter fraud in the USA in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting elections in each state.
With this in mind, since 2009, the majority of American governments have promulgated new laws that complicate the registration or ballot process.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to present photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deny the right to vote to citizens who have a court record.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The United States Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states that force voters to show photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a card.
However, there are often more than a hundred dollars to pay to get the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of individuals with incomes of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are seen as voters who are increasingly voting for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use their institution-issued photo ID in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic votes.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states sponsored laws that eliminated voter registration on Election Day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections helped register some 10 million citizens.
As a result of the measures adopted since 2009, the proportion of new voters registered in 2010 fell by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators in five other states have passed legislation aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in Florida's 2008 general election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, even though they make up only 13% of the state's voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of voters, accounted for only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring photo identification to be shown.
However, the newly introduced rules in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws passed and see them as a clear goal to influence the results in the countries decisive for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes required in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Prostate cancer screening: should the test be done or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes has erroneous results, with false negative or false positives that lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This leads to greater hesitation of the already undecided men to carry out early detection tests.
Should the test be taken or not?
We sought the opinion of two specialists.
In the studies conducted in the USA, there were numerous confounding factors between the control groups, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in mortality between patients with and without early detection.
This study also showed that with follow-up after 12 years, the probability of metastasis forming is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection has been performed.
That's why I recommend the test from the age of 50 years or 40 years, if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also at higher risk.
The most important thing is to make the right decision once a cancer has been detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient needs to be made aware of the extent of the risk of his cancer by showing him the possible options where prostate cancer can be left untreated if it does not affect the quality of life in the long term, and in these cases more likely to opt for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer do not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to their lives.
They are suggested active surveillance and offered treatment as the disease progresses.
The criteria for deciding who should and should not be treated are determined with increasing accuracy.
That's why I still recommend taking the test.
But the most important thing is to talk to your doctor to determine whether or not it should be performed.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has developed a tool that makes it possible to assess the advantages and disadvantages of the PSA test.
This document (currently only in English, but a translation will be available shortly) can be downloaded at: http://ca.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Prevention of the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure for preventing cancer.
Despite advances in research, adopting a healthy lifestyle remains the best way to reduce the risk of developing it.
It is estimated that 30% of cancers could be prevented if everyone ate well and got enough exercise.
"If there were no more smokers, this figure would rise to at least 50%," says André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
However, it is estimated that about 10% of cancers are caused by heredity.
Several also remain completely unresolved.
For the Canadian Cancer Society, the fight against tobacco dependence remains a priority, despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Smoking is responsible for 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for several other cancers.
It greatly damages people's health.
"There are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec today," says spokesman André Beaulieu.
Encouraging data: 10 years after giving up cigarettes, the risk of dying from cancer is reduced by half.
The weight
According to the Canadian Cancer Society, overweight and obesity also promote the onset of the disease.
They appear to increase the risk of breast, colonal, rectal, esophageal, pancreatic and uterine cancers.
"Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against colonal cancer," he adds.
Nutrition
The organization also recommends limiting the consumption of red meat.
In too large a quantity, it increases the risk of developing Grimm or rectal cancer.
Sausages should also be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"The latter can damage the body's cells and lead to the development of cancer," he explains.
Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the link between vitamin supplements and cancer.
However, their investigations are currently inconclusive.
According to the Canadian Cancer Society, studies on vitamin E are conflicting.
While one study found the reduction in the risk of prostate cancer, another showed more of an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer has also not yet been clearly demonstrated.
In addition, Mr. Beaulieu emphasizes the importance of talking to your doctor about your concerns and family history.
"Performing an early detection test does not lead to cancer."
Analyzing the Higgs boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
Finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the Standard Model—our best or "least false" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter—but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still lacking to be completely sure.
Still, let's assume it's actually the Higgs, as there's seemingly little risk of being wrong, and let's see what it's all about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that means that two objects cannot exist in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard, as you will hurt yourself.
Because even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state", whereby this "state" largely consists of some of its properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, called Fermione, who obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other move the bosons, an evil gang of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups, according to the Berkeley Labs website The Particle Adventure (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing): the mesons, which we will not cover here, and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
However, it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle accelerates or changes direction with an electric charge, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at that very location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be furrowed by a very large rock.
That's why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't—for example, a piece of paper would never hold itself to the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the others (such as the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What can all this research "be good for", asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to accurately study any discrepancies between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who fervently hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major flaws, as it offers no explanation for gravity (oops!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is none.
By the way: in the early 60s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle — who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous-wave laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 — has already told us that in the beginning, the laser was seen more as a "lab gimmick."
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 while working in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras worldwide and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you really never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... | Le Devoir
With its Committee on Dying with Dignity, Quebec recently discussed the thorny issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he resignedly agrees to be helped with the meal.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bringing him his medication, and offering him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is that my diarrhea be cured, as it is humiliating," he shares.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"That depends on the person's ability" to take a step backwards, he notes.
Because, according to several people who work in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these setbacks.
The patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who care for them.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But through the illness I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any more desires in life," she says, before accepting to be put on a mask to help her breathe.
Nevertheless, she expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy, in the next few days.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers offers personal hygiene and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little when you consider that one day we're all going to die.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both on the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is granted oral care with brandy or Pepsi, depending on his wishes.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," reports nursing director Nathalie Savard.
At Victor-Gadbois Home, no two days are the same.
In addition to an old man of 93 years who enjoys the last family reunion in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows while toasting in his honor, a young man of 36, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel worriedly.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when they reach the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal Area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this major inadequacy in Quebec's health care that has caused several doctors specializing in palliative care to view the passage of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe has been circulating to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before accepting to switch to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days in great pain without any action being taken to alleviate her.
I fear that patients want to die simply because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, despite the worst prognosis, several oncologists treat their patients doggedly until the last day.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped an arduous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop treatment, she replied that she regretted giving up the fight, she said.
However, she had told me that I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the caregiver for not acceding to that request after their pain was relieved by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain management.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society of Home Palliative Care of the Greater Montreal Area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain management.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which amounts to euthanizing the patient either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be relieved."
