A permanent anti-corruption unit established in 2011
Established in 2011, the permanent anti-corruption unit is also making great efforts with its troops of auditors, investigators and analysts from the government.
Then there are the police officers of the "Marteau force", which since 2009 has caused the Montreal "sewerage cartel" to be more restrained in artificially inflating contracts...
In recent weeks, it has carried out scores of house searches and made accusations of fraud and corruption against municipal officials such as Frank Tampino and Richard Marcotte, who is mayor of a suburb.
Next on the list would be Gilles Vaillancourt, who has just resigned from his position as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third-largest city.
He is suspected of repeatedly accepting bribes in exchange for public contracts.
Incidentally, engineers from the Montreal Department of Roads, as well as entrepreneurs of Italian origin, such as Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito, were explicitly accused.
The latter caused a stir by explaining to the Commission the operation of the 'system' for obtaining public contracts.
He himself spent several years paying 3% of the value of contracts received in Montreal to a Mafia-linked intermediary who transferred the money to Union Montreal, the party of Mayor Gérald Tremblay.
Mr. Zambito had a hand everywhere in the 2000s, giving more than 88,000 Canadian dollars (about 68,000 euros) to provincial parties, especially the Liberals in power at the time.
He also confessed to organising illegal fundraising for former Liberal vice-president Nathalie Normandeau.
Sewerage contracts the cost of which has been artificially inflated by him
In Montreal, the "system" of corruption functioned smoothly.
Former civil engineer Gilles Surprenant described this in detail to the commission: in ten years, he received gifts, invitations to travel, golf tournaments, restaurants and ice hockey games, as well as bribes of $736,000 from the construction company in return for sewer contracts, the cost of which he artificially inflated.
Other officials at the Department of Highways have admitted that they allowed themselves to be bribed by artificially inflating bills by 30-40% with false benefits.
In addition, an organiser of the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, has accused Mr Tremblay of deliberately ignoring a shadow budget that filled his coffers with black money.
As a result of these revelations, Mr Tremblay resigned at the beginning of November, plunging Montreal into a serious crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first Montreal legislators to sound the alarm.
As mayor of the district of Rivière-des-Prairies, in the east of the island, she rebelled from 2010 against the sale of a municipal property that was acquired for 5 million dollars and resold for 1.6 million to developers in the booming real estate market.
70% black money in election campaigns
Of the investigation that will ultimately be conducted, she says that it is "pulling a thread that makes it possible to understand the functioning of the system infiltrated by ants in order to stop the evil and denounce the culprits".
She says the procedure is "painful but positive."
We are in the process of cleaning up the wound, but we would need an investigation unit dedicated only to Montreal, as well as oversight to prevent a return of the questionable practices.
How to clean.
Regular.
Jacques Duchesneau, for his part, notes that "officials have stolen hundreds of millions of dollars", but is particularly concerned about the role of "elected officials who are aware of the tactics" if they were not involved in the fraud!
Starting from a 70% share of black money in the financing of election campaigns in Quebec, he quips: "I was told that this was only a weak copy of reality."
The Quebec government is proposing to limit donations to political parties to $100, which, according to him, would not change the situation: "As long as campaign spending is not strictly limited, black money will be circulating in politics."
He recommends a complete overhaul of the system for awarding public procurement and financing of parties: "We cannot fall lower; by getting to the bottom of things with courage, we can rebuild the house on a more solid basis with more controls and laws."
If this story damages the international reputation of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchesneau urges those who laugh at it to take a look into their own backyard...
