With Bitcoin, paying and selling is possible without a bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between the participants.
Moreover, as is so often the case in these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the conviction that the current monetary system, shaped by banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a secure exchange protocol such as BitTorrent, which allows the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers on the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
Several thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, Bitcoin's price fell to 2 dollars five months later before recovering to around ten dollars today (prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) showed interest in doing so in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to traditional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the "credits" used to advance in a video game that can be won or bought (and sometimes exchanged back) by playing.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, the trade is controlled and processed each time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the ledger, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data associated with this transaction are electronically signed by a double encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded Bitcoins are present in the account book of public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding this extra line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "chopped up".
The goal is to find the number that results in a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the correct one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money to cheat, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward will be halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but divisible to one hundred millionth, which leaves some leeway...
In addition, the difficulty of the task increases with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and the Bitcoin deposits stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, which is a real money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Major players such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others such as the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega sale" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, a company that converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions, making them cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented at the dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
All you have to do is provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend towards rethinking hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to catch on, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
In its report, the ECB also envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are now regarded as high in the event of the success of this currency.
