A constitution with a crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game from President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration that temporarily grants it unlimited power, it has decided to put all its eggs in one basket.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt his final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this plenary two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, amended several times, for almost two years now, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only created an even greater division in the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trample the law underfoot."
Its supporters assert that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to abandon their plan to explain the text to the Egyptians section by section.
For the president, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as protest rages across the country.
According to an interview with the American newsreel Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain unlimited power", the latter should supposedly come to an end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals did not comply with the request.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away, believing that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities and civil society have acted in the same way.
In order to reach a quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, the articles were mostly passed unanimously.
Commentators found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day... in the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted yesterday evening, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the principal source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, hoped to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is proof of their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy" is the response of liberals, who see this only as a propaganda strike.
According to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place via other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, especially with regard to the verification of conformity with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people who are invited to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
One can see in this the first signs of a theocracy".
The fears of liberals are also fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"At present, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics, some of whom have been trained in the French system," reassures Alexis Blouet, who is writing a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He acknowledges, however, "that there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
One refers in particular to the "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, editor's note].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on this."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticized for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In line with the military's wishes, the audit of the defense budget will not be submitted to parliament, but to a national defense council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have demanded.
The latter also express their fears about the text, which they regard as threatening freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article refers to the protection of women, said Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comforts and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons to visit Israel.
Bowing to the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding party, walking on water, calming the sea storm, and fishing.
It was here that Jesus appeared to His disciples after the resurrection.
However, most of the sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
Believers walk here the Passion or Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The trail starts at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the judgment was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands on the site where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross for the crucifixion of Jesus was made grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place for Jews – the Western Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes there, which then come true.
Take a journey to the heights
The ruins of the Massada fortress form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at an altitude of 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
All others are taken by cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there with a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an old legend, pagan gods allegedly lived on the mountaintop.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (parliament).
There are kept ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean Desert, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There is exhibited the collection of works by the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Al Basha bath, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the former visitors and bath servants.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most harrowing chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the Children's Memorial, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were exterminated in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
Upon entering the room, there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for your health
Israel's three main recreational areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red Sea and Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, bathing in the Red Sea is also done in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and people swim there all year round.
By the way, with a location of 417 meters below sea level, this unusual sea is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and therefore easily carries even non-swimmers on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural brine) and healing mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm stressed nerves.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old city of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city ran the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda here, with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is said to be good to all those who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries for photo ops.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can wander through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre now hosts evening concerts and operas.
Watchlist for tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is better not to take in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you can usually get around by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a rapid tram and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stations connecting the Lower City with the Upper Town.
Strictly speaking, it is an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough for a journey of up to 1.5 hours including transfers.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is observed on Saturdays in Israel.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is suspended.
And on Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and pubs, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and foods containing both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have a choice of different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), and fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are many well-fed cats that roam the streets comfortably and unmolested.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) to 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80), depending on the brand.
Insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the visa waiver on February 9, 2011.
"The great and powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates.
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in their homeland.
On December 1, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test attesting to knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail trade.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
You have to take not only language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be proven for both obtaining and renewing the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who obtained their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problems and protection of rights
All the examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; More than 160 centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question in the press several times before the law came into force: What is the point of all this?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring for both Russians and guest workers?
Above all, countering spokesmen for the migration authority, it is a matter of reducing the number of forced laborers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency's representation in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before their departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, under the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barrack, where he will endure months without food or documents with dozens of his peers, toiling 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"At home, you are promised one thing, and on arrival you are scammed, your passports are confiscated and do not receive the promised wage," confirms Tolib Shwaripov, head of the Tajik Migration Authority's main labor migration administration.
Don't complain, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they not only do not speak the language of the destination country, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a decent primary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect regarding the law.
Only migrants with legal status are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers continue to be in Russia illegally.
"Welcome" or "Access prohibited for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The members of the Russian police know that most of our documents are forged and we are not registered, and this leads to cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
"Don't shy away from the costs of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be forged.
Some fake certificates certifying completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Agency.
The counterfeit papers were printed with an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive them in vain: each migrant hoping to save himself the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot simply be purchased.
For now, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fail the test the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in crime extremely low
The Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs is planning to tighten the gun law for private gun owners.
This is the authorities' reaction to recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the rampage of the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
Irina Yarovaya, chairwoman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, supported the proposal and promised that the amendments to the weapons law would soon be submitted to the Duma.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "tightening the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various gun associations - demand that the authorities refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, criminal lawyer Vasily Lesnikov told the BBC's Russian service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed during six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not deter criminals from using the black market.
At present, according to the authors, any weapon can be found in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former colonel Viktor Baranez, who spent ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a web page accepting gun orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel come illegal weapons, which are stolen from law enforcement officers by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen both from police armories and directly by law enforcement officials.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons depots.
Explosions occurred frequently in many military camps.
"There is evidence that some cases involved arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Nowadays there are countless private arms factories that cannot withstand international competition and therefore squander their weapons on the black market, for example in Moscow," reports the expert.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
A particularly large number of pistols and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"They have their own, sometimes artisanal production, as well as a mafia that organizes smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the approximate share of each of the five channels in supplying the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on weapons.
According to investigators, the vast majority of illegal weapons come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market got there through the "fault of those responsible for dealing with weapons in their work," the report says.
According to the researchers' data, 17% of weapons come from conflict zones, 14% are due to theft during weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun shop, who asked not to be named, assures that weapons found during illegal excavations have not been bought for a long time because they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get supplies from an arms depot.
An ensign buys a weapon, for example a TT pistol.
The weapon is exhibited and passed through the fence.
"The dealer takes the gun into town and sells it there for 900 euros each with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, periodically carry out control purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons," adds the sales consultant.
"Like in a luxury shop"
Buyers and sellers most often find each other through acquaintances.
I had been looking at websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested that I come to the Begovaya station, where a person would be waiting for me to take me to a certain place where we could negotiate the price.
I only found out the price for the weapon there
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but you have to go there and arrange to meet with a code like "Ivan Ivanovich, who lets it be known that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I am currently even getting some brass knuckles through an acquaintance I trust.
He also only delivers the brass knuckles to me because he knows that I won't blow the whistle on him.
Newbies are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military member Viktor Baranez tried his hand at buying illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he wrote an article on the subject.
According to him, the schemes have not changed.
