No one can yet predict whether the protests will swell even further or whether they will soon run out of air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organizations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of ordinary Walmart and fast food workers, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of forming unions.
So far, this branch of the economy is hardly unionized.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called Black Friday, when sales took place in the US that attracted millions of customers, sometimes leading to scuffles.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, walked off the job and, together with unions and left-wing activists, went on strike at branches of the chain targeting low- and middle-income people.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in Walmart stores are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That's why many of Walmart's low-paid employees only shop at their own workplace.
The prices and assortment of goods made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart can often only sell the goods so cheaply because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, for example lack of forklifts or hand scanners.
Participants in the Black Friday protests demanded wage increases and expressed anger that the contribution to company health insurance had risen from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee earning $9.5 an hour couldn't afford that increase, they said.
Researchers from the University of California at Berkeley show that if the company raised the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That is about 1.1% more than they donate now for wages.
If Walmart were to pass on the wage increases completely to the customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
Compared to today, this would mean additional expenditure of only 12.39 dollars per year.
Proponents of Walmart note with satisfaction that there were protests in only nine states and these did not cause the company any losses.
Black Friday lasted in his store from 8 p.m. on Thursday until midnight the next day, and during that period, Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, Walmart checkouts carried out nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
