"So far, the brain has only been moderately outsmarted"
The topic of augmented reality, popular among followers of modern technologies, has recently been perceived through the lens of special glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a corresponding patent.
However, speaking to Shahram Izadi, head of the interactive 3D technologies group at Microsoft's laboratory in Cambridge, it becomes clear that the glasses were just a transit station for the company's scientists.
It appeals to the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please briefly describe what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes touched.
However, we want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate the radical changes of this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect because everyone is interested in motion control.
- What can we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has taken interaction to a physical level, much still takes place on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We are trying to change that, working on real three-dimensional display systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, this requires that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much more easily.
And first of all, we should get rid of those stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It's popular, but isn't it overrated?
- It is certainly not the one-size-fits-all solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform all bystanders about your actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its specific niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and concise gestures instead of sweeping ones.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that registered the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, however, the future belongs to mixed types of control, such as gestures and speech.
-How so?
- For example, would we ask me to hand you this bubble can?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- Usually I just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does this mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and cannot do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the development of new types of sensors that make it possible to capture people's reactions more accurately.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they offer good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- Based on your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your expectations of modern cameras?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, because the developers of the algorithms have more work.
Not only the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also along the Z axis must be taken into account.
Speed and the number of frames per second are also important.
Human movements are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are not enough, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our Redmond lab with an adjustable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between man and machine.
For my work I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more frames per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared emitter and the second a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could potentially solve the problem...
Or exacerbate the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera tilts to see how that helps us determine a position three-dimensionally.
- If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that in terms of applying augmented reality technology in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in your raised hand on the go, but I think the following: The best variant would be a "changing" augmented reality, in which we could switch from glasses to smartphones via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and therein lies their strength (private things only you can see), but at the same time also their weakness, because augmented reality by means of glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to mere mortals.
There is one problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands don't feel anything at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method at the moment is the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection surface.
She perceives pressure excellently!
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directional ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is currently still as weak as if someone were blowing over the palms of their hands.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outwit the brain?
Make it think that it feels what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it like that yet.
Here lies another task that we will have to contend with for a long time to come, namely to make a person who is physically in an enclosed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms and large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately outsmarted, and there are still many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes working in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: we are only at the beginning of many topics.
