Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earthlings on board go in search of a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question arises, how can we reproduce in weightlessness or on the surrogate planet?
In my opinion, there are not many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could inhabit, at least hypothetically.
"Namely Mars and Venus," says Vladimir Surdin, a research associate at the Sternberg Astronomical Institute.
However, while conditions on Mars are comparatively conducive to life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers initially dealt with the question of reproduction in space with regard to flora.
Half a century earlier, experiments had already been carried out with plants.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the slightest from the terrestrial species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to study how weightlessness affects embryo development.
A normal chick develops.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to find support; it must be able to stand on its feet and start moving," explains Vladimir Sykhev, head of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
Without a solid surface, the chicks rolled over wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not react to light and sound.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Twice we let chicks hatch and then stopped the whole thing because it is simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sykhev about the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last brood cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized and sent into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research must continue," notes Vladimir Sykhev.
After landing, the space rats had offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive instinct.
In contrast to animals, humans could do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was with Tereshkova.
The most precious thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the question: Can it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"After all, no one answered that question," says space veteran Vakhtang Vachnadze.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andrijan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Savitskaya, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, a risk remains.
We have very few cosmonauts who went well after long flights and had healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even when flying into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valery Polyakov, Hero of the Soviet Union and Hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydrolaboratory in the cosmonauts' preparation center is an obligatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a state of limbo, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Even if adults find water pleasant, it is a foreign environment; but infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders bear witness to the fact that life on land rose from the ocean.
There is a correlation between the fact that a child is in the amniotic fluid in the mother's womb for about 9 months, and that it can then get used to water more easily.
In principle, this is logical, since only 2 weeks pass from birth to the first swim.
"That's not enough time to forget anything," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
While weightlessness is a much more natural state for a newborn child, the woman cannot do without gravity.
In a state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles regress enormously quickly and thus the ability to squeeze the child out decreases.
Well, let's avoid this with birth-inducing aids.
The birth could, for example, also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is Valery Polyakov's not insignificant question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling gravity, the organism cannot form the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a suitsuit in orbit for training like an adult.
He will simply lack what is of fundamental importance to his life.
"This experiment that we are carrying out together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the fact that we will give birth to a disabled person, a completely non-conformist person," predicts the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestov.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
Eventually, however, it becomes reality when the Earthlings set off in their spaceships to a distant planet that becomes the home for their descendants born in space.
NKÚ chief: Control of the black system fails due to the fault of politics
The Czech Republic has good supervisory bodies and adequate laws in relation to public contracts, but falls behind in their application.
Speaking for Aktuálně.cz, Miloslav Kala, Vice-President of the Supreme Control Office (Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad, NKÚ), says.
"A law is never perfect, but it has to be applied correctly - and I don't think that's the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar conclusion seems to be reached by a joint inspection by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative practical example, he cites Prime Minister Petr Nečas' attitude towards the so-called "black system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls - so is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then the head of the government cannot simply come and hinder the work of the Assay Office, whose duty is to monitor compliance with the law," Kala notes.
At the meeting of the Control Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you discussed a joint Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries on public procurement were compared.
What was it all about?
This is a parallel audit that we started about two years ago.
Put simply, it is a matter of European legislation determining how public contracts are to be handled. National legislation is based on this. And finally, there is the actual practical application.
We have compared all this and, although the examination has not yet been completed, we have found very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws here may even be a bit stricter and more perfect, but the actual application is better in Germany in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to constantly establish new and more precise rules. One must also deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What does this project mean for you?
It is precisely such joint control that could help us to stop constantly striving to perfect the law and to lower and balance thresholds when this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Profitability means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But lowering order thresholds does not guarantee that we will achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we only burden the system with excessive "paperwork", and those who are looking for gaps in the system have it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remain higher.
You talk about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech Public Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an authority similar to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Auditors, which has a similar structure to ours and also has a college that is only formed slightly differently. In principle, however, both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also comparable to a certain extent, although Germany is a federal state, i.e. these courts of auditors also exist in the individual federal states - this is what distinguishes the German system from ours.
The BRH may only control federal funds that correspond to our state resources.
Public funds, which are administered by the districts and municipalities in our country, are subject to the control of the state audit offices.
As far as the German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would be reluctant to compare this without concrete information. Nevertheless, Germany is often referred to as a role model in some respects, but it certainly cannot be said that Germany is better at everything.
Is this perhaps because the examiners are better there?
Certainly not, but as I said: I don't particularly like such comparisons.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a role model for us are also struggling with problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't benefit from working with our agency, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what significance did the amendment of the Public Procurement Act have for your authority, do you already feel any effects?
In view of the fact that this amendment has only been in force for a short time, it has not yet had an impact on our audits.
Since our checks take place retrospectively, a certain delay must be expected here.
So far, we have felt the effects more in the preparatory phase of future controls - for example, we have introduced the new control instrument "Identification of risks of inefficiency" and used it to examine and analyse almost 14 000 public contracts - here the changes will of course have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, etc.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positively, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be adhered to.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to scrutiny are accountable to the promoter (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the effect that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act amounts to a violation of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
In my opinion, not in this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making.
Such a system only puts even greater pressure on bureaucracy.
Where is the way out?
First of all, let's say which way is not effective.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what does that mean exactly?
Is the black system now banned or allowed?
A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then the chairman of the government cannot simply come and hinder the work of the Assay Office, whose duty is to monitor compliance with the law.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he cannot say that we pretend that nothing is happening.
The Public Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain operations - and this is also right for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely due to formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think we are missing.
