Šimon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the end of the world taking place in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we humans like to jump on so much.
With our band The Tap Tap, we tend to make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It is a nationwide charity event that we have been planning for two years.
To do this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is predicted to end on December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00.
The end of the concerts should be around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which lies in a time zone around 12 hours ahead of us.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally probably by me, then we developed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we will hand over this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, which people can also help us with www.e-tap.cz purchase.
The band The Tap Tap, together with other performers, has also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world entitled "The end of the world falls out".
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube. Will it also be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, provided that everything works out and the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem will be sung simultaneously by all performers at all three concerts.
In addition, the anthems will be broadcast live together in a live broadcast by Czech Television.
The lyrics of the hymn were written by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, Xindl X also sings along...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we organize many charity events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What purpose does the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world benefit?
For the establishment of the barrier-free educational centre Studeo, on which we have been working for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we want to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built, into which we will then move with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What criteria did you use to select them?
We wanted to put together a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform.
Everything else can be found on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "major events" planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we are preparing an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. Of course, we also have to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems so far, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I sometimes wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad, you have a comparison of how it looks in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than here, we witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its infancy in the East.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not handicapped accessible. There, it is still unusual for someone in a wheelchair to be alone in the city center.
It is not even self-evident that you let a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, associations are also springing up there to try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what respect do we need to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still many things we are lagging behind...
It should also be noted, however, that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to be able to move independently in public spaces, go to museums, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in social events, in this we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Public respect and accessibility is one thing, but it's only when major athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come out of our ranks that things really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular. But if we go back a few years, what motivated you to form a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensively.
And since I am a musician myself and play the saxophone, among other things, I founded a music club together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our presenter, Láďa Angelovič, likes to say, it gets a bit out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; In addition, we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you achieve something and this is not visible to the outside world, your own performance does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to EU funding, we can also afford good editors, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to make it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do things differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are only a few truly unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; This is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full-fledged life, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, it is progress not only for themselves, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you can't compromise on many things and you also have to demand a certain discipline.
In my opinion, however, this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic performances, and when they realize that they have rehearsals twice a week, have to complete preparation phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm of many quickly disappears.
But that's how it works everywhere, in any band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them have been there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group. People come and go. This cannot be prevented.
Anyone who has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome.
