Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this space agency at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the member countries of the European Space Agency (ESA). Poland is thus the second member state from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's journey into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were involved in space travel, although they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's globally recognized contribution to the development of space travel was honored, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket engine was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project unfortunately remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or brake the draisine.
The information comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered projectiles.
The research was carried out by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the surviving documents it can be seen that the research had advanced to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted, of course, by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, Rohozinski's design of a photoelectric hunting missile appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocketry were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated at the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Agency (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society is in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At that time, the first satellite technology projects were already underway, and it was foreseeable that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Agency PTA tried to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-chairman of the International Space Federation.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum altitude of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests began in the Błędów Desert with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for observing high-altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor 1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm, and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport compartment with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum altitude of all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a launch weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the creation of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
