These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer emanates from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Obviously, liberal democracies are currently quickly finding themselves in a situation that Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic at the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been in disintegration, and the offices were occupied by force.
For bribes, by unlawful fraud of advantages or with stone and sword.
Corruption rampated unrestrained, and the people went to the polls with votes they had already bought." "People of character did not apply for office, so that as a result of this decline the state had no consul for eight months" ... "People really began to talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult situation was autocracy, and that a strong man had to be elected"... Appian was thinking of Pompey, but the strong man was Caesar, who permanently replaced democracy with autocracy.
As it turns out, today's society, as in antiquity, is based on the ruthless preference of one's own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
By its very nature, private capital is not in a position to recognize and enforce the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, now as then, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who make no effort whatsoever for deeper reforms.
