The Movie Argo: When It's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had maintained patronage over his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the installation of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the ensuing fiasco in the violent attempt to free hostages only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages provoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat by Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, succeeded in bringing the refugees out of Iran; they were helped by an extravagant story to conceal their true identities - they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film crew that allegedly visited filming locations for a science fiction film in the country.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez also required Hollywood's cooperation.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in professional magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time a so-called "caper movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar play such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels alternate in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which are ironic and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the conference table, in the corridors, on the phone...
With this film, Ben Affleck has achieved a remarkable reboot of his career.
A ridiculed actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime thriller Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film that is not set in the director's native Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that set this director's previous films apart from the standard of Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this intuition in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the opening sequence of the storming of the embassy is very impressive in its clarity, while still conveying the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the wrong film stick at a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story doesn't actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes helping reality - which does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or the chase on the runway, seem a bit artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its overly wide spread, due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck's film loses some of its traction as a result. It's a film that you can follow with some interest, appreciating the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70s.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive today and as proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the all-powerful and omniscient secret services are.
Guidelines for ballooning, bananas and circus inflation
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually calls a survey on the most absurd bank charges, decided this year to organize the competition "Most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop".
"This is the idea that came up with the EU's recent plan to introduce a 40% quota for women in the management of large European companies," Patrik Nacher, who is in charge of organising this survey, told Právo newspaper.
Among the nominated absurdities is, for example, the judgment of the European Court of Justice on the unification of insurance rates for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they objectively pose less risk to insurance companies.
"More incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated until the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place by the end of February 2013," Nacher said.
The controversial EU regulations include the mandatory addition of bioethanol to fuels, which is subsequently harmful to nature, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain a relatively small amount of this hazardous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs much more expensive this year.
In the past, criticism has also been levelled at the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the ban on the sale of conventional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under pressure from this or that lobby from trade and industry, whose demands in Brussels are usually represented by one or more member states (for example, the Czech Republic is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks even with veto threats).
Lobbying interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest trading class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have a "curvature anomaly".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was merely harmonising inconsistent national standards that would hinder trade.
The standards on fruit and vegetables have already been softened by the EU against the resistance of some countries, pointing out that the previous directives would lead to food waste.
One candidate for victory in this poll may be last year's EU regulation, which, according to balloons, must be labeled when selling them that children under the age of eight may not inflate the balloon without adult supervision.
The EU referred to an American study, according to which balloons are the leading cause of suffocation of children.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to 14 years of age when using fairgrounds.
Curious ideas also exist at home
Also relatively absurd is a directive that affects European civil servants themselves - anyone who has an official function in the EU is not allowed to use the term Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the issue for Greece and must instead say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com nominated the EU regulation on the extent of food stocks on the territory of a member state in addition to the above-mentioned absurdities.
The EU thus set the maximum level of food stocks that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic, for example, then exceeded the specified volume for canned mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a high fine.
The survey organisers were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or by the idea of giving funding for applications for funding.
These ideas, of course, did not come from Brussels, but from Prague.
"We are disadvantaged by the fact that we have no sea.
We will apply to the EU for reimbursement," said the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he argued that the grain harvest had been very high and the state warehouses were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
Since the Czech Republic has another way to seaports, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros, according to Palas.
The European Commission finally accommodated the Czech Republic by organising a tender for the purchase of cereals from countries that do not have access to the sea.
Funding for applications for subsidies was offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Regional Development under the leadership of Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), specifically funds for the preparation of grant applications to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
Although regulations are easily the target of criticism in the member states, the EU's efforts to regulate and thus also to ensure the effectiveness and development of the entire European Union deserve more recognition, according to some experts.
According to these experts, a more serious problem is rather the EU funding for projects that have absolutely nothing in common with the deepening of European integration, but which were forced by individual member states during the budget negotiations.
Emotions are also aroused in this country by the fact that the Czech Republic, like other member states, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific designations of traditional products and does not always win this battle.
Although the Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky" after a six-year struggle with Germany and Austria, our manufacturers had to rename the Inländerrum (Tuzemský rum), whose tradition dates back to the 19th century, "Tuzemák".
The term rum may only be used for products made from sugar cane distillate, not for products made from sugar beet.
In the official list of products registered in the EU, the company of the world-famous cheeses Feta and Gorgonzola, Lübeck marzipan or Parma ham now also includes Karlovy Vary rusks, carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, or Saaz hops.
Pardubice gingerbread or Hořice rolls can boast of an EU trademark.
