MVRDV architects prove that true adventures are not only in the mind - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I think the building is funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large company, says: "Yes, it's beautiful, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one today voluntarily goes to one of these old-style libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town on the outskirts of Rotterdam that hardly needs to be visited, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant municipality has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to reconstruct the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro notes as nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library was needed!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architecture firm MVRDV, master of daredevil bar charts and producer of witty, often cynical buildings, took the matter with his usual composure and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around in amazement and shrugging its shoulders, the cheeky Maas stacked his exquisite souvenirs into a pyramid in size and ended his actionistically underpinned speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So this is my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has been filled up.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project has also been nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small-town retort, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunned, ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory, is enriched by a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long road to the book
The first impression: book Eldorado under cheese dome.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, the true pleasure of space and reading opens up when climbing the topography on foot.
The all-round glazed interior is bright and clear, the fired brick floor and the elegant street lamps speak unmistakably the language of a public town square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park benches, dogs and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
"Normally, the bookshelves are along the façade, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and turned the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books is cleverly used: In the middle are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and building services center.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall coverings, sometimes parapets, sometimes staircase railings.
Optics, haptics and smell are foreign.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard.
And so one day we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Friesland farm.
For many years, a millimetre-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in these quantities - into four-centimetre-thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, resilient material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-meter-long hike, you will be rewarded in the literature café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heating and cooling is done with geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass lintel, the sun shines only briefly into the interior, even on sunny days.
The wide glued wood beams, which stand transversely to the glass façade, serve as shading and absorb a large part of the solar radiation.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal inventory.
For the time being, this is intended to fill the optical gaps in the library, which is not yet fully stocked - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept worked.
The shelves are filled to the brim.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for adornment.
MVRDV has thus succeeded in achieving the supreme discipline known in technical jargon as identity creation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained from voting on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
DW: At the beginning of the week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for observer status for Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes that's true.
This is because it is currently changing its foreign policy away from a policy that was managed, so to speak, by the US, towards a German foreign policy.
To make matters worse, Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans find themselves caught between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to that.
I think they are still approaching their role, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like that of France or Great Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean in concrete terms from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions on national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other great powers, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the attitude to the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to offend the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That definitely plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to attach too much weight to it, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it definitely plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I think there is a great deal of understanding for the German position in Europe and even in the US.
Therefore, I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even earn a certain respect.
Because it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and its interests must be considered.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly spoken out in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic politics, these differences have always existed.
I think that the Obama administration secretly understands the European position.
But due to the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, take this position publicly.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always appear.
If you look at relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of its most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they can't be part of a broader line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe towards a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, if only because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that the Germans are aware that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or is it still difficult for Germany to take the lead?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a bigger role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, every time Germany assumes a greater role, various anti-German feelings are released.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
That's actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this sense, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It has to be receptive to different neighbors and opinions and that's not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European politics is steadily declining, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else is left there?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America conduct joint research on the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, as is Polo Ralph Lauren.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind it hides a name officially registered in China, which, however, has nothing to do with the original companies.
Nevertheless, it enjoys protection as long as the actual namesakes do not complain.
And even then, it is not clear whether they will be right.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloch, an attorney at Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in IP infringement in the Far East.
Every week a new case lands on my desk.
A few additional letters are enough for the imitators to register their trademarks.
So Gucci simply becomes Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can enter Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in this way, such as the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a folder with registrations from the trademark office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
It is well known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property.
In the big cities there are multi-storey department stores that sell almost exclusively fakes.
Pattloch's cases, however, are different: On behalf of his clients, he is taking action against Chinese companies officially obtaining the right from the trademark office to use a designation that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call this "Bang Mingpai", a passenger brand.
The word is based on "Bang Dakuan".
This refers to women who catch rich men.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt
"This is damaging to business, you have to fight it," Pattloch demands.
"The brand is watered down, the unique position disappears, the image damage is enormous."
The financial losses and litigation costs of the affected industries run into the millions, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to the market research company CLSA, China is the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing with a volume of 15 billion euros per year.
But deletions of dubious entries in the trademark register are difficult to achieve and cost money.
The proceedings can take up to nine years, with an uncertain outcome.
Pattloch reports cases in which the court dismissed lawsuits because after the long duration the disputed name had become a "market reality".
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he even has to pay the plagiarist money because he infringed his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal dispute with construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that recently acquired German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
The Chinese are therefore still allowed to use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Volvo buyer Geely originally used a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW; the dispute was settled, Geely had to change it.
The fashion manufacturer Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore, who made the famous crocodile look in the other direction.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt.
The trademark office CTMO in Beijing admits that there were bottlenecks there in 2010 due to insufficient staff and space resources.
In the past year, however, one had returned from the "emergency situation in the workflow to normality".
For example, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings has fallen by 22 percent.
Almost 57,000 such cases have been closed, 75 percent more than in the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 appeals are still waiting to be settled in the office.
Tackling this costs a lot
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This is a record and means that China leads the list of new registrations around the world for the tenth time in a row, the authority said.
This also applies to the inventory of all valid trademarks, a total of 5.5 million pieces.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in fees were collected.
Put simply, this means that each application costs an average of 1280 yuan or 160 euros.
Tackling this costs many times over, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarist.
The Germans were able to achieve that his illegal production of imitation motor vehicle parts was dismantled.
However, the imitator continued to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich, says that they themselves failed to do so because family names cannot be protected in Germany.
The trademark office CTMO rejected the opposition of the Munich.
In the next two instances, Freudenberg was right, but the opponent continues to fight to this day.
You have to be extremely careful
Now the matter is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident of bringing the matter to a good conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says: "The procedure is extremely complex and costs us a lot of time, money and nerves."
The internal costs could hardly be quantified, the company archive even had to look through one-hundred-year-old files to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg offered the other side a "high six-figure euro amount" to settle in vain.
"This shows how much this is worth to us," says Wentzler.
The dangers in the Far East even threaten to spill back into Europe.
Namely, when imitators secure unprotected trademarks there.
For example, a Chinese manufacturer wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather in Germany.
The Group has long since given up this business area, but was nevertheless able to avert registration.
"You have to be extremely careful," says Wentzler.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch advise German companies to be very cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark rights, but foreigners should "register everything that is somehow worth protecting in China," as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, it can be much more expensive than registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg is defeated in the last act of his brand drama, then you would probably have to pay the other side royalties for your own name, explains Wentzler.
Or we will be forced out of the market in the segment in question.
World AIDS Day: Stomp, sing, help
In Heidelberg, the choir rehearses Imbongi - and in Swaziland AIDS orphans are happy about it.
The story of a connection that overcomes far more than 8733 kilometers.
First there is the pounding: cowboy boots, basketball shoes, women's pumps and men's slippers look for the beat on the parquet floor, find it quickly.
One-two-three-four.
Only then do the voices of the singers slowly swell - alto, bass, tenor and soprano - press, beguile and pursue each other.
And Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old conductor, almost lifts it out of his cloth shoes when he brings them together with his smooth, wild gestures.
It's Monday evening, in the music room of the Institute of Medical Psychology in Heidelberg, the choir Imbongi is rehearsing a new song.
About fifty singers have come, between 23 and 69 years old, from human geneticists to househusbands.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each choral part has a different text and this also in a very foreign language: Zulu, which is spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and parts of Swaziland.
Helping people to help themselves
Unaids, the United Nations programme to combat AIDS, estimates that there are around 34 million people infected with HIV worldwide.
Of these, 23.5 million people live in southern Africa.
There are 245,000 AIDS orphans living in Swaziland.
More than 40 percent of the population is now HIV-positive.
The association Voices for Africa has found sponsors for 180 AIDS orphans in the village of Esitjeni in Germany.
70 of them attend secondary school.
For 15 or 20 euros a month you can take over a sponsorship.
It guarantees the child school fees, school uniform and a warm meal daily in the Gogo Center.
Imbongi means storyteller or praiser in Zulu.
Nobody can speak the Bantu language fluently in this room, but he can sing.
For almost ten years, the choir has been practicing songs in this foreign soft language and occasionally bringing them back to where they originally came from: to the south of Africa.
Because 8,733 kilometers as the crow flies from Heidelberg, in the northwest of the Kingdom of Swaziland, there is the village of Esitjeni, which depends on the vocal power of the German choir.
Forty percent are infected
About 2000 people live there, some still in simple mud and straw huts, most of them are children.
More than 300 of them no longer have parents because they have succumbed to the HIV virus.
Esitjeni shows on a small scale what ails the whole of Swaziland: highest HIV infection rate, lowest life expectancy worldwide according to Unicef.
Circumcision of the male foreskin, which has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by half, is hardly accepted by the population.
More than forty percent of people in Swaziland carry the immunodeficiency virus, and dying in their mid-thirties is not uncommon.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir discovered the village, but above all the Imbongis saw many children on the streets, who not only lacked parental care, but simply everything: food, clothing, education.
Without a school leaving certificate, you certainly have no chance in a poor country.
Initially, it was the private commitment of individuals to send a child to school for a few euros a year and to enable him to have a warm meal a day.
But just one year later, the choir founded the association "Voices for Africa", which has been taking care of the AIDS orphans in Esitjeni almost professionally ever since.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs include HIV, human pappilomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies belong to the parasitic STIs.
Who are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are mainly found in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five of all syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydial infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea and human pappilomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - nevertheless: Around 20 percent of new HIV infections are attributable to this group.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections occur much more frequently than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In this country, human pappilomaviruses are also common in adolescents.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are notifiable.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 cases in 2001 to 3698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2700 cases.
This is about a tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
The infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, lower abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not offer one hundred percent protection.
In some cases, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through smear infections and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially in the case of frequently changing sex partners.
If diagnosed early, most STIs can be cured and long-term consequences avoided.
