The drive through the Talysh Mountains is wildly romantic.
The minibus rumbles along the winding road, past densely wooded hills, raging rivers and simple farmhouses.
Everything is green and juicy, you might think you are in the Black Forest.
But this is the deepest south of Azerbaijan, the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
Here lives the Caucasian ethnic group of the Talysh, of which not much is known, except that they perfectly speak Persian as well as Azeri and are very long-lived.
The final stop is Lerik.
The small town boasts overly massive architecture from Soviet times, which does not want to fit into the picturesque mountain landscape.
Tourists from Europe hardly come here, the journey from Azerbaijan's capital Baku is too difficult.
For the 323 kilometers you need eight hours, because the road is only single-lane.
The fabulous wealth that the country owes to its oil in the Caspian Sea has not yet arrived here in the province.
But Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
"Baku became famous in May with the Eurovision Song Festival – and next year we will have a festival of the oldest people in the world here," says Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the Museum of Longevity, probably the only one in the world.
Here is documented the vita of about eight dozen Talyschen from the area, older than 100. Fatulayeva points to a black and white photo.
This is my grandfather, he was 120 years old.
Fathered a child at the age of 136
But the controversial star of the museum is the shepherd Şirali Müslümov, who is said to have turned 168.
However, there is no birth certificate.
And in view of the oldest documented person, who lived to be 122 years old, Müslümov's age seems extremely doubtful.
"He was born here in the region in 1805 and died in 1973," Fatulayeva explains.
The man had been married three times and had 23 children, at the age of 136 years he is said to have fathered a daughter.
So did Şirali Müslümov miscalculate his age by a few decades?
But Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard of the very elderly in Central Asia.
"There are also a striking number of very old people in some areas of China, in Japan or in the Hunza Valley in Pakistan," says Scholz, "even in Sardinia live extremely many very old men."
Due to a lack of documents, however, no scientific proof of age could be provided, especially since civil status registers were missing.
Butter melted every day
The fact is, however, that the people of the region around Lerik strikingly often reach a biblical age.
There are currently 20 people older than 100 years.
So why do so many very old people live here in the south?
The Azeri travel guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains this with the special genes of the Talysh.
Museum director Fatulayeva, on the other hand, believes that it is due to nutrition.
But the fact that the high-calorie diet of the Talyschen, who love meat, bread and especially dairy products and many of whom drink a glass of melted butter every day, should be so healthy, does not seem exactly plausible from a nutritional point of view.
Or is it the original way of life that keeps people young? Rubaba Mirzayeva lives in Cengemiran, a tiny settlement not far from the city of Lerik.
With its 97 years, it is still comparatively young for these latitudes.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the entire Caucasus region.
She sits on the floor with a butter churn, which she tirelessly rolls back and forth.
Eight people live here under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and a daughter, both long since grandparents.
Two toddlers also jump around.
In the kitchen, tea is prepared for the guests, which is served in the typical, belly-shaped Armadu glasses.
Mirzayeva's white teeth are perfectly lined up, under her headscarf she hides long, dark blonde braids, which her son proudly reveals in front of us.
I always washed my hair with milk, so I never ran out of it and kept their color.
"I never used shampoo either," says Mirzayeva.
Monthly pension is enough to live on
She only ever ate what came from her own farm, tomatoes, potatoes, peas.
In my whole life, I have never once bought groceries in the supermarket.
Then she talks about her husband, who was in the army.
It was worst in the period after the Second World War.
But everything got better when the "beloved father" Heydar Aliyev took over.
The propaganda sounds strange from the mouth of an old woman.
But the cult that is driven around the father figure of the nation, who ruled his country like a dictator, knows hardly any borders in Azerbaijan.
He was in power until 2003, when his son Ilham took over.
After all, there is no need among Azerbaijan's elderly.
Mirzayeva receives 230 manats (about the same amount in euros) per month as a pension, an amount on which one can live well.
And perhaps Mirzayeva's long-graying son is right: "The elderly are highly respected in our culture."
They live in the midst of the extended family, are loved, cared for and are happy.
