Now is the time to let the people decide at the ballot box in which direction the country should go.
A majority for the Islamists' draft is considered certain.
"The word human rights does not even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious about this forced constitutional process, which should have lasted until February and involved all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when it was imprisoned or tried under Mubarak.
Not because he shares their worldview, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution," he complains in an interview with the "Welt am Sonntag".
Morsi's expansion of power to all three powers in the state made the lawyer resign.
These measures are blatant violations of the democratic rules of the game and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president is de facto suspending it," Saeda complains.
But without civil society organizations, a democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which views the ideological struggle on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could take its revenge.
A demonstrator on Tahrir warns: "You are giving birth to a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most foul-smelling fish in the world?
Norway's five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest standards of living - not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country's secret to success have something to do with the local appetite for rather foul-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, damp sportswear.
And leave them there for a week.
That's how you have to imagine the nasal smell of rakfisk, one of Norway's great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There's snow, spectacular scenery – and that persistent smell in the air that just doesn't want to go away.
Rakfisk is salt-sprinkled trout that - depending on how smelly you want your fish to be - is fermented in water for up to a year.
In Norway, when darkness falls over the country and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to, well, really captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then wash it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station, but also organizes the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk general".
Around us, people eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," says Havard.
The spirit can displace the smell.
I taste some appetizers.
If you avoid bringing the rakfisk close to your nose, it's not bad - like sushi, which has had quite a long bus ride.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, far poorer Norwegian era, when there were no refrigeration facilities and fish was soaked in airtight saltwater barrels in autumn.
In the depths of winter, after a long fermentation, it was taken out and consumed, no doubt with the help of alcohol-dampened senses.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and comprehensive health care.
Even from Sweden, the old rival that not so long ago was far richer than Norway, immigrants are pouring in.
Rakfisk is seen as something important – an essential, if strong-smelling, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the more expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs a proud 10 euros.
Norway doesn't often make it into the world press, and most people don't seem to mind.
They still hate to name Anders Breivik - the racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it refers only to the "July 22 incident."
Norwegians find it difficult to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Since the early 1970s, Norway's wealth today has been largely due to the growth of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays of ripe rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blond hair and piercing blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Their English, like most people here, is impeccable.
We are not very boastful, we do not like bragging.
Norway has been very careful with its oil wealth - a large part of the industry's returns are invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the Great Depression, when everyone threw money around they didn't have, Norway kept its wallet tightly locked.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, we're happy," says Anna.
"And, of course, eat rakfisk," she adds with a lighthearted laugh.
I'm standing in the snow lining up for another dish - I've had enough of rakfisk.
Such a moose burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat tastes good to me.
But in the evening the smelly fish is on the menu again.
The hotel where I stay is one of several venues that organize a rakfisk dinner, where guests can vote for the best - or perhaps the most challenging - fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a bow-tie-clad showmaster surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
The spectacle is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
People clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by aquavit.
But maybe it's the harsh haze of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
As Mexico's president-elect Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office, the BBC's Will Grant analyses the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad.
Even on better days, this is always a congested city, but on Monday a ring of steel was built, blocking off several major traffic routes to the capital and wreaking havoc on the streets.
However, the goal was not to disrupt commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential armband and take over the leadership of the nation.
He faces a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has performed well economically, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already claimed 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My administration is strongly committed to reducing violence," Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office.
I will propose a new security strategy to help us achieve this goal.
Before he was on an equal footing with the US president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, people like to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to him the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built, which are a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques bearing his name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting change from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for Pena Nieto's party, the PRI.
Especially in terms of security and economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects the opposition's accusations that the new president lacks substance.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an outstanding statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway overpasses and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to combat drug gangs operating in neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In the last two years alone, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left behind on a patch of wasteland near a large landfill.
During the administration of Governor Pena Nieto, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that surpasses even that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murder of innocent women.
Pena Nieto's critics believe that he has at least not adequately addressed the problem of femicide during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the run-down neighborhood, Irinea Buendia fights back tears as she shows me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes that she was murdered by her partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed like her body had been washed," Senora Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and rigor mortis had already set in.
While her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is placed next to a cross bearing a single word: justice.
But exactly this, according to the family, has been denied her until now.
The authorities treated me as if I was a gossiper, troublemaker, complainer.
They want people to simply accept their judgment and keep their mouths shut.
"But that's not possible when there were so many formal errors and omissions," she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential armband on Saturday, he will also be assuming a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crime over the past six years, and the new president has promised to pay special attention to this issue during his tenure.
"I hope as president he is what he was as governor," says PRI congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But this is precisely what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Prosecutors allege: Bradley Manning did not complain of abuse
Prosecutors deny Bradley Manning's allegations that he was mistreated in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks to dismiss the charges due to excessively harsh prison conditions
The private of the US army is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents
Prosecutors on Friday sought to establish that Army Private Bradley Manning — charged with the largest disclosure of classified information in U.S. history — missed several opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he allegedly suffered while in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month term in Quantico, Virginia showed no complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held following a request by the defense to dismiss the charges - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh prison term - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The US Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein went through with Manning the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been held under increased conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein questioned him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as "very professional" overall.
The forms, Fein said, contained no complaints of abuse, though officers had questioned Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officers had discussed them with him and indicated that they were dealing with them. However, they were not recorded.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) 'No problems,' and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he didn't complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to have his observation status downgraded to "injury prevention."
The military said it assigned him this restrictive status — which is one step below suicidal prom — to protect him and others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was okay and get rid of the observation status for injury prevention (...) to achieve what I consider to be a higher quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Naval Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he considered suicide in Kuwait and once fell unconscious due to the heat.
Not being allowed to know what was happening to him or in the outside world was stressful.
"My world shrank on Camp Arafjon, on this cage," Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to keep moving, because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards could no longer see his face, he was woken up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, the judge also questioned Manning about an allegation he had made in his testimony on Thursday - for example, he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico for one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to wrap himself in his blanket during this count.
When questioned on Friday, Manning said he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself. He admitted, however, that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night. He had previously tried to show an official that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning told the officer he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning testified, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his experiences in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted at his trial before the military court. This is scheduled for the beginning of next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses, while other charges deemed too extreme will be appealed.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend. The prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon maintains its position that Manning was detained in accordance with the regulations that apply to all detainees held under the highest security at Quantico.
Charges against Manning include aiding and abetting the enemy, unlawfully publishing intelligence on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing public property or documents.
If found guilty of all charges, he faces life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants — they remind them of hard times, he says.
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are caught between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and arrived at passport control when perplexity spread through me.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure which one to go to.
I grew up in Central California and have been called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Irish" or my friends in New York "Italians".
Later I chose "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least well enough to hold my own in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I can't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and stood in line for Extranjeros.
I thought about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all the issues expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trafficking.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy. It is one reason why Mexicans today are just as likely to stay in Mexico instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico's war against the drug cartels, although he gave no details.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never give it a single thought to the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the country's leadership at gunpoint to cede more than half of its territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries, not minutes, memories of this event cannot be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the mildest criticism of Mexico, one hears complaints -- in the Mexican press and among the country's elites -- about how Americans are harassing their neighbor's sovereignty.
And the children of Montezuma embark on the warpath.
And yet, in reality, Mexico's greatest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There are more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is because at one point in our family tree, a person — perhaps a parent or grandparent — wasn't given a chance in Mexico and emigrated north.
And in most cases, this person matched a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our allegiance is to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may now have been living the American dream, attending good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we are living – not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but when it comes to our loyalty, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeat and look down on us for not being Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn't find ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a comfortable life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is tension between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are — and Mexican Americans resent them.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel they don't belong to one country or the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but you are not rooted in either of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I was supposed to learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and sections of the educated middle class want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want to appoint Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" to Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great it is to visit this country and put pressure on the political leadership to strengthen its ties with Mexico.
Now.
That's not going to happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, rampant corruption, and drug violence, many of us aren't so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans hold a grudge for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar for peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to nip such hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual finger-pointing, countless buildings have been reduced to rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed -- and for the first time, rockets from Gaza have hit near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate may finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism in view of the current situation seems anything but appropriate.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, this week's fighting has strengthened die-hards on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though his group itself suffered heavy losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are crammed into one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And Hamas leaders may conclude that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to attract powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power once considered Israel's closest Muslim ally, has sided with Hamas, as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Cheering Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah holds power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist character could face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
In particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt – by far the most populous and important Arab country – on Israel's southern flank has permanently altered the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until its overthrow in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
By contrast, the Brotherhood is in-law with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
Militarily, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has proven itself and many of the Hamas rockets have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more peacefully.
In diplomatic terms, the United States remains steadfast in its position. Many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalation of violence.
Israel has fared well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers, thanks in no small part to the barriers that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of a possible Palestinian state. These protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared contrary to international law, but are constantly being expanded.
Netanyahu is doing well. His Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group ahead of the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why coddle these deceitful Palestinians and give them their own state?
If they were indeed in control of the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets just like their allies in Gaza?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail. But the Arab Spring could thwart their plans.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little sympathy for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties at home.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower is unlikely to help the new Arab governments repair their economies.
That pragmatic President Morsi teamed up with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign -- and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis, too, should think more long-term.
As the rest of the Arab world takes tentative steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder keg that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and as the Arab population grows, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push back Hamas in Gaza will increasingly take their diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need an external impetus
The correct answer is the one advocated by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, most of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states where Israel cedes territory for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, along with Turkey and Qatar, must now halt arms shipments to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial swaps and a common Jerusalem.
Outside Arab nations should also persuade Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must do his part to persuade Israel to negotiate.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems that he is equally averse to involvement.
But this is an unfortunate, short-sighted prospect.
The United States has a vital interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws for uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on plain green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world's first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia. This replaces brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with graphic images showing sick body parts and infants and children sick from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, from next Saturday the only difference will be between the packs in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font.
Australia is thus introducing the world's strictest regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to discourage young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
The government assumes studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at the age of 26 are 99% likely not to start afterwards.
"You can already see in children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to advertise with their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek. She cites studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have little impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar moves.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would encourage black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, however, say the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the unbearable packaging has increased enormously since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed to challenge the laws in Australia's Supreme Court two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stock.
It's a good deal for us.
According to experts, the catch lies in the popularity of social media with the very demographic targeted by the plan.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV commercials, banned them from acting as sports sponsors and forced most retailers to stop displaying cigarettes in stores. Now tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local businesses and sites, but has no control over international sites.
"If you market tobacco and only have a small area left to advertise your products, you can't avoid the Internet," says Becky Freeman, a healthcare researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media outlets like YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has seen an increase in brand testimonials written by "ordinary people."
You have to ask yourself: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that he even records a video for them - or does a marketing agency have anything to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of marketing, the industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations - those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, even though none of the countries engage in major trade with Australia.
A WTO ruling is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to impose photographic warnings in 2001.
These have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures do not influence me.
I just ignore them.
"You just take a butt and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette pack with a photo of an oral tumor printed on it.
Honestly, there's only one reason I would quit, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the tobacco store King of the Pack in Sydney's city centre, says uniform packaging has made it difficult to replenish his shelves.
"It used to take me an hour to sort in a delivery, now I need four," Yu says.
"The government should have simply banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said okay, that's it, we'll shut down," he adds, visibly angry.
In an ever-electrified world, it's nice to be bored
This Thanksgiving, I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane broke down due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to think about boredom.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty annoying – even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and, of course, tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts cite boredom as something positive.
If it's up to them, it's okay for us — and our kids — to get bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us these days are almost constantly staring at one screen or another, we no longer reap the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yes.
And no.
I will come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing free time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011), doesn't see it that way.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
The walls of Pompeii's house are decorated with Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfying job but not being able to do so."
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
With apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a "disruption of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time passes slowly."
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored individuals see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed individuals see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're just having trouble concentrating.
In their study, "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention German," which appeared in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape in which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room, which had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at a low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who listened to the barely audible television reported feeling more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could not find a reason for it, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
If, on the other hand, you are engaged in a monotonous activity - "such as searching for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can be distracting and help you not feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that fidgeting and doodling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat them by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to hang around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a booming loudspeaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "boredom susceptibility scale" in the 1980s.
On the scale are statements such as "Many things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys get boring more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida — especially when it comes to the need for more and greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tired bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teens and their parents with a pager seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored at school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they weren't in school.
However, only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, that he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their daily routines.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it leads people to take extreme physical risks and succumb to gambling or drugs to alleviate them – studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you to do something else," says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do.
When you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you'll be happy.
But television can provide feelings of happiness in the short term, but these evaporate again in the long term.
So if you hand your bored child an iPad, you can dissuade him from boredom. However, it has not learned to entertain or control itself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control is transferred from one situation to another".
The child not only learns to entertain, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of them.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant sprinkling of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often. But boredom is the agonizing, relentless desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to switch off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it's hard to keep busy once the noise has stopped."
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old community college student and soccer player, is on trial in southeastern Colorado for an offense that will soon be legal in that state: possession of a few chunks of marijuana and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was summoned for possession of drugs and drug paraphernalia — trivial offenses, each with a $100 fine — and given a court date.
"We are treated like criminals," Orozco said.
But is he one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state's decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the answer to hundreds of minor drug offenses depends less on the law than on location.
Hundreds of marijuana-related misdemeanors are already being dropped here and in Washington state, which approved similar measures.
Police authorities no longer prosecute adults over the age of 21 for small-scale possession. This will be permitted by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado's more conservative counties have vowed to pursue existing marijuana offenses and are still citing people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to block new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
"This situation is evolving so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next," said Daniel J. Oates, a police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
And regulators in Washington state are also scratching their heads helplessly.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline of 1 December 2013 in mind.
Washington believes that Colorado is definitely ahead of most states when it comes to marijuana regulation. There, the drug was legalized first for medical purposes and then for personal consumption.
"Colorado has a more regulated market. The state is therefore well suited for orientation," says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Spirits Commission in Washington State.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve as a rough guide.
"We don't have a real precedent to follow," he adds.
The Washington Act, called I-502, goes into effect on December 6, marking the end of a gray area where the state licensing system does not yet exist, but ownership is legalized.
And unpleasant practical questions need to be clarified during this time - such as how the state requirement of "reasonable access" to licensed marijuana should be reconciled with the prohibition of cannabis shops within 300 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
"Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area," said Ben Livingston, spokesperson for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his staff in Aurora stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses against people over the age of 21, and that police would not seek criminal charges for these offenses "as of now."
Chief Oates added that police will continue to enforce city regulations regulating medical marijuana growers and drug traffickers will continue to be prosecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck takes a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his agency would continue to pursue marijuana possession cases, mainly to persuade users to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people face trial for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana, although many have also been charged with other offenses.
"Our agency has a duty to prosecute violations that were criminal offenses at the time of the crime," Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are ambivalent even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters opposed the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer report adults for possession of smaller amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all outstanding ownership cases.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes," he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that reconciling personal marijuana use with the complexities of government and the legal system would not be easy.
And the conflicting reactions across the state revealed a profound dichotomy among local officials about the great green experiment.
District attorneys are a "cultural barrier," says Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney who represents defendants on trial for marijuana offenses and serves locally as a spokesperson for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
"They have spent such a large part of their lives prosecuting people for this that they still cannot accept legalization," he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana such as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are being touted as national model cases for drug legalization.
As advocates and state officials prepare for an age of legal sales, they are also nervously awaiting instructions from the federal government to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana as a criminal offense at the federal level.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Justice Department will give in.
Despite several high-profile arrests of medical marijuana users and sellers, the federal government has largely allowed medical marijuana sales in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while detectives are unlikely to kick down doors to seize smaller quantities of the drugs, they are likely to resist tolerating the legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not even waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before election day, some local governments approved moratoria on new marijuana businesses, although they may not open for about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, passed a six-month ban that is expected to be passed next week.
"We don't want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level," said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our municipality voted against this change in the law.
We are guided by what the church has chosen, not by what the state has chosen.
Many questions remain unanswered.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only today's university students are attacked for their views
It had always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended what I once considered the largest temple of knowledge in the world, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks of moving into Worscester College in the late eighties - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my bags again and caused the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the next room.
Author A N Wilson mischievously declared that I left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I did, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had been bullied for only one reason - a reason that seemed all the more narrow-minded and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my late father, Woodrow Wyatt, had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I had been a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate right students is suffering similar persecution.
The organised and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now reached such proportions that a group of them last week called for equal equality protections that benefit gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked, and declared undesirable" because of their political views.
They are demanding a place on their college's equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Their situation was exacerbated by a recent BBC Two documentary about political students, Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right, which portrayed Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It showed, among others, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the conservative student association of the University of Oxford, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and flaunted a silver-colored suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are seen as "scapegoats for introducing higher tuition fees."
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the University of Nottingham's Conservative Students' Association, told a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing left-wing tendency in universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other."
Samuel Roberts, 21 and a history student at Corpus Christi, who initiated the request for greater protection, believes such a climate is "unpleasant." 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of the Oxford Conservative Student Association, says she has seen growing opposition to moderate right students among JCR members.
"This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members," she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
Hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university had voted not to award an honorary degree to Margaret Thatcher – a former student – due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have startled even Stalinists.
In the first days of the freshman week, where new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what will happen to come.
My experience was that the tutors not only tolerated the ridicule of Tory students, but even happily participated in it.
Political issues such as the miners' strike, privatisation and the government's rejection of sanctions against South Africa's apartheid regime found their way into the wood-panelled rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events, I was asked to translate French texts from the 18th century into English. I had not been prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled.
Pitt was a small man with a face made of cake batter, and quite spiteful.
"Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students giggled.
Tears welled up in my eyes.
"I suggest you take a few French lessons in your free time, so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt growled at me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That night, I was sitting alone at dinner in college when someone lightly tapped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is what it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it will be worse for you.
Most Tory freshmen pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub I later tried to pretend.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs Thatcher on everything.
This trick was to prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who ironically attended Eton College, which was considered conservative, said to me, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig."
You are polluted.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They beat each other, right?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I only be able to meet like-minded people after dark?
Should I have to turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years ahead stretched into a purgatory of ostracism and isolation in my mind's eye.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a Conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and small-minded, and rejected it for his Marxist-determinist historical perspective.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
"You're not going to be happy here," he told me.
I began commuting between Oxford and my parents' house and found refuge with more outgoing friends and family in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in his forties, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said meekly.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming spires.
Even my communist friends always showed impeccable manners.
His wet eyes clouded.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory supporter, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his convictions.
During a tutorial the following week, where another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Although I secretly melted with shame, I admitted that my parents had brainwashed me and called them "old fools."
The relief was short-lived.
It was my father who put the final nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At the time, he was writing two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my captors gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You are welcome to call me a whiny floppy tail.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragically is that it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but to this day hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to celebrity"
