The most difficult profession in the world: the human workhorses of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the wearers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, stony paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to climb down to the floor of its crater every day, where the sulfur-containing gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping stone paths.
Although it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2386 meters, the exhausted porters need more than 40 minutes to climb at turtle pace, keeping their balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Once at the top, they make their way between the tourists, who photograph them like circus monkeys, and walk three kilometers with the tiring heavy baskets to the scales, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the deposits in the volcano and (never better) its workers since 1960, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for each kilo of sulfur.
She then sells this to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each way," explains Anto, who usually makes three distances a day.
For each distance he needs three hours, after which he is completely done, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable reward for such an almost inhumane effort, however, is three times what he would earn from fieldwork.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid a day during the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as the sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I took her to Java,  to convert them to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
For the past three years, 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already left its first mark on him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
"I'm going to work here for another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man, but punished by life, could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a donkey.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other porters and gets up every morning at two o'clock, because the sulfur also emanates at night, where his characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 porters load the baskets of sulfur onto their shoulders on the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur mining to save costs and does not supply any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
They also do not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera that the guardians of this nature park demand from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human donkeys, along with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros).
"This work is for the animals and not for humans," protests Madrusin, a stocky, 42-year-old porter who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as possible" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners are trapped in the thick pillars that rise from the crater, the men are so tough that no one complains of serious illnesses ... of course, except for the usual breathing problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders, which have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik is only able to carry 50 kg at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks along a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, in which some teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the eldest, at the age of 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but the poverty continues generation after generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: that of those who work as human workhorses at Kawah Ijen.
