It is the biggest problem in this country.
When it comes to reproduction, we are the worst in the world, so we realized that it was an issue we had to take care of.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as marketing perfume with pheromones or organizing speed dating evenings (quick flirts).
It is possible that many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought: Why don't we do something as creative as possible to address this problem, like composing a rap?
1,2 Children
The one who does not take this issue lightly is the government of Singapore.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and distributes tax benefits.
But so far everything has had little success.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was above 2 – also known as the replacement rate – was in 1976.
So why aren't Singaporeans having more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Authority, says this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities."
"This has allowed people to have a lot more options in terms of life goals and priorities, in addition to getting married and forming a family," she explains.
These changes in social realities have contributed to the increase in the number of single people and the delay in marriage and birth, resulting in a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration to counteract the reduction of the population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where barely concealed xenophobia flourishes against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and failing to integrate.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the ruling party in Singapore last year achieved its worst election result since independence.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has the well-known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs, and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
It is already having an impact on the housing market.
The Department of Urban Development has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that are allowed to be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show great sales success.
However, there is concern that they may promote the lifestyle of the single person and that they will discourage construction companies from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of real estate firm EL Developers, says his "shoeboxes" sell much faster than larger housing units.
They're so popular, and the units sell out days and even weeks faster than the larger units.
As a result, they are much better for our cash flow.
He admits, however, that the new standards give clearer guidance to developers, who were previously faced with obstacles if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for a rise in the national birth rate, conversations with Singaporeans working in the financial district suggest that they won't have much impact.
"People are very stressed, the apartments and also the education are expensive, which is why it is postponed by many," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It's important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women cite their careers, the stress and cost of owning and raising as reasons for not being able to have children.
That's why Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children – there is so much the government can do.
The offline private offline is online private
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property private or "that area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference".
What is private for someone under the age of 16?
How is this definition applied to his everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he exposes himself to when he makes known situations on the Internet that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who frequently use the Internet.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "something very unique" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when applied to social networks.
"I wouldn't reveal my deepest secrets in one post," says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the meaning of "private" on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he's had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother is allowed to know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also pass my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that's not of me or someone doing the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, of nudes, of crimes, or to write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge assures to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers in Twitter.
Most are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I logged into Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I'm just uploading them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can quickly talk to relatives far away or with friends," he says.
When asked, he replies that he would never accept an invitation from a stranger.
Even if someone recommended a stranger to him, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teen has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space, and Ask. In Ask, he admits he doesn't know 20 of the people he added to his friends list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to the boy, no one gave him any hints or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone pushes me or demands them from me, I just remove them from my account," he admits.
José reached out to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to experiences known today as cyberbullying.
The acquaintance of a friend was blackmailed in a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never found out who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim did not close the user account.
"He only did it privately."
He then explains a series of steps to securely configure a user account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would do that if I don't like him or I want to wipe one out of him.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key
Marielos Porras, an English teacher with a degree in education and learning, believes that in order to orient children and young people, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a medium for searching for information; but with the appearance of these pages, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's degree in education at Yale University and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants," coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach them when we are still learning," he says.
He explains that it is a complex issue "because we require them to have a defined criterion about what can be disseminated, published or said, at an age where the maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be picky when the most important thing for them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and young people what privacy is is to ask them questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then mentions some possibilities: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger. So why are you doing it on the internet?
Or: Would you like it if someone published a photo of you, like the one you posted by a friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission beforehand if you labeled photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Does everyone need to know what you are doing at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they need to trade online as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
"Someone off the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educational advisor, comments that it is essential that parents carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
If they understand all the sections, they will have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, the age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, children need to be reminded of the lesson "Thou shalt not talk to strangers."
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was announced in advance and theoretically should be signed by the seven leaders present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the Sixth Ordinary Session of Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially said they would hand it over after the retreat, but said afterwards that it would be published on the Peruvian government's website at some point.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information on the summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting was broadcast in the press room without sound with the message "private session, limited audio".
The little information circulated among the journalists was obtained from the press officers of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press secretary.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets demanding more information.
After that, the presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the Humala Declaration and not the official document concluding the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South America-Arab States Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, too, despite strong press requests, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced in advance, was not published either.
On the official website of the ASPA you can see that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that information systems were in place for journalists, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to adopt a ruling by the Hague Court settling a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICJ, which begins on Monday in The Hague, to hear the pleas of both sides in the trial launched by Lima against Santiago.
"We will follow and carry out the verdict on the differences we are currently bringing to this international court," Humala said together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that abides by international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts," Piñera added, shaking hands with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia filed a lawsuit against the Bogotá Agreement, following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a grave mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the rulings of this International Court of Justice.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, of Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 following the ouster of its president, Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, in which he announced that 16 decisions had been taken and the lines of action had been set for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total investment amount of 17 billion dollars.
Commenting on the decisions taken, he said that the countries of Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we will extend the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be promoted to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organized, transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant traits, but should serve to expand our productive output and show our peoples a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new forms of economy," the Peruvian president said in a statement.
Among these projects would be five Peruvian ones, located on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, two of which are intended to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its readmission into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico on Saturday to treat the maritime conflict respectfully, following an ICJ ruling questioned by Bogotá.
"Maybe tomorrow (Saturday) I will meet with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all these avenues - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he underlined.
"I hope to be able to say to President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers also met ahead of the summit to adopt the 2013 action plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the region's defence.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru holds the temporary chairmanship of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from the integration of its citizens," says Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, confirmed today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal, whereby "South America can indeed learn something from Europe."
Correa, who attended the 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), held in Lima, told state television in Peru that Europeans "killed themselves in World War II and other conflicts" and "today are practically a fatherland."
In this sense, he defended the project to create a South American citizenship, which the member states of Unasur promote.
"The free movement of citizens and workers must be achieved in all South American countries, as is already the case in the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary sectors seeking a return to the past," he warned.
The President of Ecuador also endorsed the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OEA) with the aim of reducing the influence of Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those that have signed the San José Convention on Human Rights.
Those who teach never commit themselves to anything, and in return, we South Americans always sign everything.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is based in Washington and funded by the United States," he said, alluding to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assured that he did not regret this decision because he had not betrayed his principles, but had fulfilled his "deep democratic values and views on human rights".
He added that at the time there were "reasonable suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and his procedure would not be followed."
He also criticised the Swedish judiciary, which had asked him to be interrogated on his territory for an alleged sexual offence, while "Swedish jurisprudence allows this by means of a videoconference that could have been carried out via the Ecuadorian embassy in London."
Correa explained that there was a risk that Assange's health and mental state would be affected.
"Since he is in our embassy, I have not spoken to him, but the ambassador has informed me that he has a slight problem with his lungs, but not a serious one," said the head of state of Ecuador.
However, there was a risk that he would suffer physical and psychological damage because he was trapped in a confined space and could not perform physical exercises outdoors.
"That would affect the health of every person," he added.
Correa stated that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at Ecuador's embassy in London was to grant him carte blanche to travel to Ecuador, and that it was in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe. He underlined that there had been talks with London to find a solution for the imprisoned founder of WikiLeaks.
We do not deal with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe, because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is conducting a series of cases at various European instances," he said.
And "if Britain grants this carte blanche tomorrow, I think it's done."
And if Sweden interrogates Mr. Assange at Ecuador's embassy in London or via Skype, as Swedish jurisprudence allows and has been done in other cases, the problem is solved.
Correa took the opportunity to affirm himself as a defender of press freedom, saying that what he does not tolerate is "mediocrity, evil intent and lies that invalidate freedom of expression."
"The biggest enemies of press freedom are not the evil and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who seek profit and blackmail," he said.
In this sense, he congratulated himself that Ecuador is no longer dominated by such journalists "nor by the bankers or hegemonic and bourgeois countries," anticipating that if re-elected, he would "deepen the revolution in order to continue the path in this right direction."
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in Unasur at least until its next elections, arguing that the organism "must remain tough and not allow opportunism or a coup d'état disguised as legal" because it "has destroyed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay."
The President of Ecuador also considers the wish of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime borders between the two countries now and after the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which favoured the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime borders between the two countries to be "absolutely justified".
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They must be dealt with comprehensively so that they can be overcome and looked forward.
He also relied on a good conclusion to the disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile before the same court, saying that "it is right for Latin America to appeal to international bodies if both countries undertake to accept the verdict, even if it is very harsh."
Referring to the possibility of running as a candidate for Ecuador's next presidential election to win his third consecutive mandate, he said he sees this possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although sometimes it is also very difficult."
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 elections, he would retire from political life.
Power has never interested me personally, but in circumstances as unjust as Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement believed that it was me who guaranteed this likely victory, so I have to live up to that responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last term as president, after which I will retire from public life.
This is true even if we lose.
"That's decided," he said.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the President of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I have just spoken with the Vice President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro. He told me that he had traveled there for a planned, routine treatment, and that he was expected to be able to return to Cuba after the election campaign.
"It does not mean in any case a relapse in the state of health of President Chávez," he commented.
The Ecuadorian leader attended today in Lima the 6th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which ended with a call for greater regional integration to ensure sustainable progress, equality and security.
The cause of dying due to AIDS today is too late
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the test result was confirmed: HIV-positive.
"It was like a bomb hit," he says of the moment he received the diagnosis, which the doctor "tried to mitigate" without apparent success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to find out about it; and this with such dedication that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he came in 1994 after several fights.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 90s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmas.
At that time, even the director of a clinic of the IMSS avoided saying goodbye, "because it led to a dead end."
At that time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome even with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who do not know about their illness and for whom the virus has already caused damage and exhausted their immune system, and who are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the appearance of the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment on time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," explained the head of the HCG's HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, saying that this information was supported by a prestigious scientific publication in April this year.
Infectious disease and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that while AIDS is not a death sentence, years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of people's immune systems at the start of treatment, and that those who are not addicted to drugs have greater chances:  up to 30 years for a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years for a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above means that anyone who is diagnosed HIV-positive at the age of 25 "can easily live to be 75 years old as long as they are under control," this professional explained.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA's annual report), it is still true that since the appearance of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients recorded in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May this year there had already been 187 deaths; however, it is assured that there has been universal access to antiretroviral medicines since 2005.
- So why are people still dying from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so it is in our hospital.
At least for the past 12 years, we have not had any problems with the supply of medicines. The problem is that people come into a very advanced state because they do not know their state of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have a concomitant infection. In order to influence global mortality, earlier diagnoses are needed, which is why massive detection tests must be offered to all individuals who need to do so."
This proposal is approved by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco) and also by patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test carried out in a private laboratory, for the sole reason that it was made by a friend of his, who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had Kaposi's sarcoma (a cancerous tumor).  which is one of the usual complications.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they are going to die and don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, then better burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I do a lot, I have an active but responsible sex life, I take care of my health and that of the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today in the context of the worldwide AIDS Day.
They should take the test if they belong to the risk group. The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big gaps between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places, "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; in the past they were handed out individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Young people at risk for new infections include young people.
"Why do you need them?" is a common mockery of social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health system, which young people do not want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He proposed reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should not only be located behind the counter, but in dispensers in public toilets of facilities that are frequently visited by young people.
Promiscuity is not to be promoted.
They should not be paid for the beer and motel, as the governor Emilio González replied to the question of whether condoms would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality doesn't look like that; it is best to bring the condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity," he said.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks 4th nationally in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in HIV.
92% of cases of infection occur via sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV because for every registered case there are 4 or 5 people who do not know.
After the United States Court of Appeals upheld a ruling that does not recognize the restructuring of the liabilities of the Vitro Group, which was achieved through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, an ominous precedent is set for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has payment problems.
It could therefore be said that the procedures for the survival of the companies that Mexican laws allow do not apply in the land of stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the June 15 recognition of the verdict by Judge Harlin Hale at the Bancarrotas Court for the Northern District in Texas leaves Mexican companies helplessly exposed to the confiscation of their property across the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens the door for Mexico's largest glass manufacturer to appeal to the United States Supreme Court over three inconsistencies.
While the judge of the case points out that the creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy law of the United States, the Court of Appeals of the Fifth Circuit, based in New Orleans, initially says that the main proceedings are the commercial bankruptcy dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings of companies with a transnational profile is not known.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created for this purpose, with the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment states that, without the votes of the companies, after recognition of the debts in the bankruptcy estate which Vitro's branches had with their parent company, the necessary majority for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
In fact, vitro is not the first case in which this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities among companies in the group have been confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Federal Institute for Commercial Bankruptcies).
It is also true that, after deduction of the votes of the branches, Vitro's creditors, the creditors who brought proceedings against Vitro in the courts of the United States, namely the Geier funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for its difficult situation from 2008 onwards in the context of the great economic crisis in the United States, which dealt blows to the country.
For this reason, the González Sada family appeals to the same Court of Appeal so that the vote takes place in plenary, i.e. by all the judges, because only three of them voted.
If this is not upheld, the Cerciorare appeal will be lodged, which calls for a review of the proceedings by a higher court, in this case by the Supreme Court of the United States.
The serious thing about this case is that the court left aside a document sent by the government of Mexico under the figura amicus curiae (friend of the court), which describes the procedure carried out by Vitro under the Law on Commercial Bankruptcies, indicating that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries.  to comply with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
It is also noted that the country has submitted to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules laid down in cases of cross-border insolvency, which guarantee equal treatment between debtors and creditors.
Two-band carambola: a blow for vitro and for the country.
General balance sheet
After several months of stalls in the complaints filed by Mexico's air transport unions against former owner Gastón Azcárraga Andrade, accused of fraudulent administration, the Asociación Sindical de Pilotos Aviadores (Air Pilot Trade Union Federation) has finally made progress.
