Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The globetrotter of basketball, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, was associated with basketry for more than 60 years and has travelled all over the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large intellectual collection of the history of the country's basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being confined to a wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for 6 years, whether as a player of lower classes, player of the first national league, agent and leader in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Federation.
"All my life I put on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the federation in the 90s," Reyes recalled during a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he met with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.  dwells.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those that recall his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, where he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-managing director or managing director of the club.
"Those were my best years, which I enjoyed the most, because I had the pleasure of being part of eight championships of vaqueros since 1967, be it as managing director, co-managing director or coach.
These were many fulfilling years, including the five championships in a row from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye with a championship in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincy's debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a very good administrator, took over," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me: "I have a very strong and 2m tall player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and one of our best throwers.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had made one championship possible for Bayamon, Gausse would make for another.
The championship of vaqueros with Gausse was granted to him, but already from a distance, because in 1988 he was already at the top of the association.
At that time, he preferred to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember the first time we beat the USA at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, which should have been bronze if it hadn't been for that Canadian referee who let us repeat the last play for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as is the one who won against the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is the team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and gave the U.S. team a fight, like when they won bronze against us at the World Championships.
Not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz) were back in that team, but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quixote" Morales, who could not be there in 1990 due to a knee injury.
One team that may not have been the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which gave us great pleasure, was that of the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina in 1995.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner as a replacement for the suspended players due to the events at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against all forecasts.
Who was Puerto Rico's best player?
That was without a doubt Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level like Piculín.
And this without taking into account his career in the various leagues in which he has played.
Who was the best coach from Puerto Rico?
This is a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
Of the boys, I like the work of Leo Arill very much.
What do you think is the best thing you have achieved in the association?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN in the early 90s up to 17 teams in one season.
What is left for you to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as regionalizing the lower categories.
That the boys in Ponce, for example, only play in their area and only meet teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Today, children make unnecessary trips and games.
At least I see the result of the prescribed training and courses for coaches, table officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like listening to music, watching videos of music from my time on YouTube, enjoying my grandchildren, and going to a basketball game every now and then.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always by my side.
Larry Hagman is dead
Larry Hagman was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas) and became famous worldwide with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R". in the television series "Dallas", where he played a ruthless, insidious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of '80s' greed, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications, according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked most," the family said.
Larry's family and closest friends were in Dallas with him for Thanksgiving celebrations.
Linda Gray, who played his wife's role in the original and sequel series, was with Hagman when he died in Dallas Hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving, and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992, and he admitted that he had been drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was detected in his liver and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas", Hagman became known on television as a nice guy in the years 1965 to 1970 with the sitcom "Charming Jeannie" of the television company NBC.
There he played astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is turned upside down when he meets an attractive "djinn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live at his home.
He has also starred in two short-lived comedies, such as "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His cinematic work included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the charmingly despicable J.R. that made Hagman a superstar.
CBS's dramatic series about the Ewing clan and other characters around it aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan "Who shot at J.R.?", which was intended to create anticipation for an episode full of emotions, where the character of Hagmann was almost killed, led to international speculation, and millions of dollars were bet in betting houses.
Thus, the series reached an audience record at that time.
When the answer became known in one chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million viewers, who turned "Dallas" into the second most-watched entertainment program since the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was Kristin, the sister-in-law of J.R. (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who had shot.
J.R. had impregnated her and threatened to portray her as a prostitute if she did not leave town. But others also had reasons for wanting him dead.
Hagman interpreted the role of Ewing as a corrupt, insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a devious businessman and unfaithful husband who sought to have his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) admitted.
"I know what's supposed to be on J.R.'s gravestone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should read "Here rests the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing".
This is the only deal he didn't win.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as an "enormous personality on and off screen."
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of devotees in the world and remains in our hearts for those who have been fortunate enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the television channel TNT.
The recording of five chapters for the second season was completed, and a sixth chapter was being filmed, the channel informed.
There was no immediate explanation from Warner or TNT on how the loss of Hagmann would be treated in the series.
Born in Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who performed classic works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Martin was still a teenager when she met Larry during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on the stages in New York at the beginning of the 50s, after which he served from 1952 to 1956 in the air force in England.
There he met and married the young designer Maj Axelsson.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and they lived for a long time in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoir "Hello Darlin: Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
"I didn't write anything that I thought could harm anyone or affect them in any way," he told the Associated Press at the time.
After the liver transplant, he advocated for liver donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist anxious patients.
"I advise them, give them courage, I meet with them when their operations are imminent and after," he explained in 1996.
I want to give them some comfort, such as "don't worry, it's a bit uncomfortable the first time, but you'll be fine".
He also campaigned against smoking and participated in several campaigns.
Start of the course studying the "end of the world"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
Every semester, when the religion professor decided to hold a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible fish hook: the end of the "long backward count" of the Mayan calendar on December 21, which many people believed meant the end of the world.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect in the following two months: the destructive Hurricane Sandy, which some have dubbed "Deudarmaggedon," and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists believe the apocalypse is beginning.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If someone analyzes what happened in the world today, as if we were thirty days away from it, that would be a really good period.
And he reminds us that the bad is good for those with apocalyptic mentality.
And he's not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, which was supposed to be the last in history.
In Temple, Associate Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas spread over time," he said, as well as the way hypothetical scenarios that lead to a particular human behavior are offered.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month, students analyzed films with apocalyptic content and examined how they compare to real life.
"I tried to educate students about what's possible, probable, credible, and impossible," Wacker said.
On the University of Pennsylvania's main campus, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an associate professor of art history and anthropology, have formed a team to offer a course simply titled "The End of the World."
"We're not recording 2012 so we always have the option to be able to hold the course again in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "imminent doom", students have to study, create projects and take final exams.
In Penn State, the final exam is held on the eve of the apocalypse, which is why students have no choice but to "keep working until the night when the world supposedly ends," Restall said.
The courses were very popular.
"There were no places left in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, which filled up with 35 students.
For weeks before the start of the semester, we received e-mails from students asking if there were still places available.
The students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It's fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old Rutgers-Camden student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey.
The apocalyptic sectarian or religious mentality is really just a matter of comfort or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, says he's seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class where this is taught," he said.
I enjoy it.
But none of the students interviewed — and less a professor — said they believed in the last date of Dec. 21.
"Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and in some ways we're discrediting it," said Julie Zeglen, a student last year at Temple, 21 years old and from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key item on the calendar, Restall said.
He notes, however, that there is an apocalyptic fear in Western society that goes back several centuries, when people responded to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has increased this speculation.
"Elsewhere, people don't think that way," he says.
This is mainly the case in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a religion professor at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, is quick to answer the question of whether he would know of a course on the "end of the world" there.
"The Philippines is not participating at the end of the world," he wrote, alluding to an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall pointed out that over the years there have been many days of last judgment, saying that if nothing happens on December 21, "people immediately think of a new date" or philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the end of the world will come.
Students and professors take this date lightly.
Several said they wanted to go to celebrations about "the end of the world."
"Maybe I'll call some friends so we can laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
